Fig. 4
 depicts the surface morphology of the HB, H1, H2, and H3 hydrogels as well as how the concentration of N–CQDs affected the morphology of the produced hydrogel. It was discovered that as the quantity of N–CQDs increased, so did the porosity increased. Therefore, the porosity for HB, H1, H2, and H3 was 8.88, 13.54, 14.74, and 36.45 %, respectively. The synthesized versions of HB, H1, H2, and H3 are hollow sponges with rounded pores that have pore sizes of 72, 13, 15, and 19 nm and surface areas of 5.86, 1.55, 2.4, and 5.36 nm2, respectively. In comparison to the others, H3 hydrogel has a larger surface area and pore size. This might be the result of rising N–CQD content having an impact on hydrogel shape (Table 1
).
